metadata.name: 4rtiu5 #38
metadata.description:
Wiki

A circle is a shape consisting of all points in a plane that are at a given distance from a given point, the centre. Equivalently, it is the curve traced out by a point that moves in a plane so that its distance from a given point is constant. The distance between any point of the circle and the centre is called the radius.

Name

So, I kinda have a thing with language so I tried to find a funny mix of "art" or "genart" and "circle" or "radius".
I ended up using "radius", scrambled it a bit which became "arduis" and replace "ard" with "art". 
The 4 and the S mean like "4 us", hence "4rtiu5" :-)

Project

There aren't much properties that are set, except for "dashed lines" and "blurred gutters". I had a lot of fun making this and was amazed by some really great outputs myself, I hope you guys like it too! :-)
Cheers üçª

metadata.name: Act One #65
metadata.description:
Act One, where the mannequin says ‚Äútake me home and I will dance for you forever‚Äù.

This work is an exploration of using motion capture data to create digital paintings, and a little belated birthday ballet for #fxhashturnsone. 
20% of primary sales are donated to Three.js.
 
Keyboard Controls:
[P] Play / pause the dance. By default the dance is paused after a few seconds to render a painting.
[S] Save the current view (live mode).
[V] Capture a short webm video (live mode).

Mouse Controls (while dancing): 
[left drag] Rotate
[scroll] Zoom
[right drag] Pan
[right click] Save image

Best viewed in a desktop browser. The output may be different from the preview image if your frame rate is low, reducing the size of the browser window can help improve the frame rate.

Made using Three.js, canvas API and WebGL2.
The 3D model is based on https://sketchfab.com/3d-models/mannequin-dances-ballet-a24678a81a6f4b6d8f8ba0eb1a78e58b, using motion capture data from dancedb.eu. 
Test in Chrome v107.0.5304.107 and Safari v16.1.
License: CC BY-NC-SA 2.0

Created by elsif, 2022.11.

metadata.name: Artifact #331
metadata.description:
This project is about uncovering artifacts.

Each piece is determined by approximately 15 parameters. This allows for a multitude of possible forms, and each iteration is an artifact to be discovered within the multidimensional space.

This work is focused around discovery. It is about exploring the space of the algorithm, shedding light on its many forms, and sometimes finding artifacts of the real world embedded within them.

Technically, this work is a composition of three primary elements: Voronoi tessellations, orthographic projection, and the depth-sort algorithm.
The latter of these is integral to the rendering mechanism. It works intuitively, drawing distant objects before near objects, evaluating the distance of each object according to its geometric center. It does this precisely, and in doing so, it can produce interesting visual artifacts, drawing some shapes in an unexpected order.



This has been a fascinating study, bringing light to unreal shapes and forms, and uncovering artifacts in an impossible space.

I hope you enjoy it,
Nat Sarkissian





Technical Notes:
- Append ‚Äú&mag=N‚Äù to the end of the URL in live mode to specify a resolution multiplier. It will render the image N times larger than the size of your window. If you have specified anything greater than 1, a download will start automatically once the rendering is done.

metadata.name: Sweeping #69
metadata.description:
Sweeping is a piece in which I explore the uses of noise fields. Using them in the most cliche way possible, but trying to make something unique out of that.

What started out as an innocent weekend project grew out to be quite the piece, which is why I am publishing it here.



Sweeping uses the GPU of your machine for its shading, which means it won't run particularly well on mobile devices. My recommended way of viewing this piece is on a PC with a dedicated GPU.

---

- Double Click to open a User Interface
- In the UI, you can toggle the paper texture and export

---

Made with p5js + webgl by Wouter Missler, 2022.

metadata.name: Tumble Down Light Factory #318
metadata.description:
Tumble Down Light Factory is an interpretation of light installations & murals.

It attempts to trigger the feeling of coming up on a new block in a new city to discover an unexpected piece of art that is stories tall or entering a new room, knowing there will be a projection dominating the space with its light and color.

This is an abstract distillation of those things and those feelings.

Each composition is initially drawn to a hidden ‚Äútemplate‚Äù canvas which is sampled and then rendered on the main canvas in various ways after applying some transforms to give it some depth (and so you can actually see it.)

Viewing in full-screen is nice. You should try it.

T : Save hidden ‚Äòtemplate‚Äô image
S : Save current resolution
1 -> 5 : Save low -> high resolution

metadata.name: fx(splash) #120
metadata.description:
To celebrate fx(hash) turning 1 year old I've created this token as a part of the #fxhashturnsone event! It's a playful and colorful token symbolizing the experiences I've had with this platform.


The piece uses shaders to generate it's visuals which means that outputs will vary from device to device, and the preview might not look the exact same as your live view.

For that same reason I do not recommend running this piece on a mobile device as the shaders can be quite heavy and blurry on lower-tier hardware. My recommended way of viewing this token is on a pc.


--

To open the export menu double click the screen. Here you can export in a multitude of resolutions.

--


50% of primary proceeds will be donated to the processing foundation, learn more about them here:
https://processingfoundation.org

Made with opengl shaders and p5js by WootScoot, 2022.

metadata.name: Up Above #257
metadata.description:
This piece is inspired by the feeling of insignificance. This feeling, which we all share and feel at some points in our lives is often referred to as negative. But I feel quite the contrary, this feeling is quite beautiful, as it shows small parts together can form something big.

We are but a speck in the universe, like a grain of sand on a beach, like a single drop of water in an ocean, like a single leaf on a tree. But together we are a forest, a river, a sea. Together we are the universe.

Feel free to explore this piece for as long as you want, and feel free to export it in any way you like, and use it for thing like prints, and, of course, I'd love to know about them :)

---

To export your iteration, click the menu bar at the bottom of the screen and press either the "Export current" or "Export custom" button.
